\ array ( v1 ... vN n -- arr ) — gather the top N stack items into an
\ array, preserving order and duplicates.

\ basic gather
1 2 3 3 array .                      \ [ 1 2 3 ]

\ order is preserved (unlike set)
10 20 30 3 array .                   \ [ 10 20 30 ]

\ duplicates are kept (unlike set)
5 5 5 3 array .                      \ [ 5 5 5 ]

\ mixed types
"a" 42 "b" 3 array .                 \ [ a 42 b ]

\ empty array
0 array .                            \ [ ]

\ gather leaves items below the count alone
99 1 2 3 3 array . . cr              \ [ 1 2 3 ] 99

\ length via size
1 2 3 4 5 5 array size .      \ 5

\ round-trip through @i
7 8 9 3 array 1 @i .                 \ 8

clear
\ array-of ( init n -- arr ) — n-element array filled with init.
0 5 array-of .
99 3 array-of .
"x" 4 array-of .
0 0 array-of . cr                               \ [ ]  empty is fine
1 -5 array-of                                   \ (negative length rejected, not a wild memcpy)

clear
\ basic
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 3 take .
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 0 take .
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 5 take .

\ clamp: n > length yields the whole array
[ 1 2 3 ] 99 take .

\ clamp: negative n yields the empty array
[ 1 2 3 ] -2 take .

\ empty source
[ ] 3 take .

\ set source produces an array of the first n in sorted order
< 5 1 3 2 4 > 3 take .

\ result is consumed: stack shape is ( source n -- result )
1 2 3 [ 10 20 30 40 ] 2 take .
.s

\ composes with other words
[ 1 2 3 4 5 6 ] 4 take size .
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 3 take reverse .

\ failures
[ 1 2 3 ] "x" take
clear [ 1 2 3 ] take
5 3 take

clear
\ basic
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] reverse .
[ 1 ] reverse .
[ ] reverse .

\ reverse is its own inverse
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] reverse reverse .

\ set source produces an array of items in reverse sorted order
< 5 1 3 2 4 > reverse .

\ composes
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] reverse 3 take .
[ 1 2 3 ] reverse size .

\ stack shape: ( source -- reversed )
1 2 [ 10 20 30 ] reverse .
.s

\ failures
5 reverse
"x" reverse
clear reverse

clear
\ ---- skip ----
\ basic
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 2 skip .

\ boundaries
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 0 skip .
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 5 skip .

\ clamps
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 99 skip .
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] -2 skip .

\ empty source
[ ] 3 skip .

\ set source: yields the trailing portion of the sorted items as an array
< 5 1 3 2 4 > 2 skip .

\ composes
[ 1 2 3 4 5 6 ] 2 skip size .
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 1 skip reverse .

\ ---- last ----
\ basic
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 2 last .

\ boundaries
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 0 last .
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 5 last .

\ clamp: n > length yields the whole array
[ 1 2 3 ] 99 last .

\ empty source
[ ] 3 last .

\ skip + last is the identity over a full traversal
[ 1 2 3 4 5 ] 2 skip 3 last .

\ ---- failures ----
\ skip is built atop take, so its errors surface as take's
[ 1 2 3 ] "x" skip
"x" 2 skip
[ 1 2 3 ] "x" last
"x" 2 last

clear
\ basic
[ 1 2 3 ] [ 4 5 6 ] concat .

\ either or both empty
[ ] [ 1 2 3 ] concat .
[ 1 2 3 ] [ ] concat .
[ ] [ ] concat .

\ self-concat: dup then concat doubles the array
[ 1 2 3 ] dup concat .

\ set source on either side: items in stored (sorted) order, result is an array
< 5 1 3 > [ 7 8 ] concat .
[ 0 ] < 5 1 3 > concat .
< 1 2 > < 3 4 > concat .

\ stack shape: ( a b -- ab )
9 [ 1 2 ] [ 3 4 ] concat .
.s

\ composes
[ 1 2 ] [ 3 4 ] concat size .
[ 1 2 ] [ 3 4 ] concat reverse .
[ 1 2 ] [ 3 4 ] concat 2 take .
[ 1 2 ] [ 3 4 ] concat 2 skip .

\ associativity (over three arrays)
[ 1 2 ] [ 3 4 ] concat [ 5 6 ] concat .
[ 1 2 ] [ 3 4 ] [ 5 6 ] concat concat .

\ failures
[ 1 2 3 ] 5 concat
5 [ 1 2 3 ] concat
clear [ 1 2 3 ] concat
clear concat

\ flatten-array: deep flatten of nested arrays; a flat array returns unchanged
[ 1 2 3 ] flatten-array .                      \ already flat -> as-is
[ [ 1 2 ] [ 3 ] [ 4 5 6 ] ] flatten-array .    \ array of arrays
[ 1 [ 2 3 ] 4 ] flatten-array .                \ mixed scalars and arrays
[ [ 1 [ 2 3 ] ] [ 4 ] ] flatten-array .        \ deeply nested
[ ] flatten-array .                            \ empty
5 flatten-array                                \ non-array argument errors

clear
\ sort ( arr -- arr ): a NEW array ordered by the system total order (val_cmp) —
\ the same order =, lt, and sets use. Duplicates are kept; the source is unchanged.

\ floats: ascending, duplicates kept, negatives and non-integers
[ 3 1 2 1 3 ] sort . cr             \ [ 1 1 2 3 3 ]
[ 5 4 3 2 1 ] sort . cr             \ reverse input -> ascending
[ -2 0 -5 3.5 1.5 -5 ] sort . cr    \ negatives and fractions ordered, -5 twice
[ 42 ] sort . cr                    \ single element
[ ] sort . cr                       \ empty

\ already sorted is a fixed point
[ 1 2 3 ] sort . cr

\ idempotent: sorting twice equals sorting once
[ 3 1 2 ] sort sort  [ 3 1 2 ] sort  = . cr   \ 1

\ functional: the source array is not mutated
[ 9 7 8 ] dup sort drop . cr        \ [ 9 7 8 ]

\ strings: lexicographic; a prefix sorts before its extension; duplicates kept
[ "pear" "apple" "ab" "a" "apple" ] sort . cr

\ mixed tags group in tag order (float < string), ordered within each tag
[ "z" 3 1 "a" 2 ] sort . cr         \ [ 1 2 3 "a" "z" ]

\ nested arrays compared element-wise (val_cmp recurses; shorter prefix first)
[ [ 2 ] [ 1 ] [ 1 0 ] [ 1 ] ] sort . cr   \ [ [ 1 ] [ 1 ] [ 1 0 ] [ 2 ] ]

\ symbols order by interning order, not alphabetically (val_cmp compares the
\ interned offset) — included to document that, not as alphabetical sorting
[ :gamma :alpha :beta ] sort . cr

\ a set yields its elements as an array
< 3 1 2 > sort . cr                 \ [ 1 2 3 ]  already ordered, projected to an array

\ a vector sorts ascending, shape preserved, source untouched; NaNs go last
[ 2 1 ] vector sort .
[ 3 1 2 ] 3 1 matrix dup sort . .
[ 5 4 ] 1 2 matrix sort .
[ 3 -1 1 ] 3 1 matrix ln sort .

\ === errors ===
5 sort . cr                         \ error: not sortable
[ 1 2 3 4 ] 2 2 matrix sort . cr    \ error: only vector-shaped matrices sort

clear
\ argsort ( m -- m ) or ( arr -- arr ): the sorting permutation — element i
\ is the source index of the i-th smallest value. A vector keeps its shape;
\ an array (arrays.h2o) orders under val_cmp and returns a float-index array.
\ Ties keep index order (stable ranks); NaNs go last in index order; the
\ source is unchanged.

[ 30 10 20 ] vector argsort .       \ [ 1 2 0 ] as 3x1
[ 1 2 3 ] vector argsort .          \ [ 0 1 2 ] already ascending
[ 3 2 1 ] vector argsort .          \ [ 2 1 0 ] reversed
[ 7 ] vector argsort .              \ [ 0 ] single
[ ] vector argsort .                \ 0x1 empty
[ 5 4 6 ] 1 3 matrix argsort .      \ [ 1 0 2 ] as 1x3, shape preserved

\ ties break by source index: the two 1.2s keep their order
[ 3.5 1.2 9 1.2 ] vector argsort .  \ [ 1 3 0 2 ]

\ NaNs last, in index order (ln of a negative is NaN)
[ -3 1 -1 ] vector ln argsort .     \ [ 1 0 2 ]

\ ranks are argsort applied twice
[ 30 10 20 ] vector argsort argsort .   \ [ 2 0 1 ]

\ functional: the source vector is not mutated
[ 3 1 2 ] vector dup argsort drop .     \ [ 3 1 2 ] as 3x1

\ an array argsorts under val_cmp into a float-index array
[ 30 10 20 ] argsort .              \ [ 1 2 0 ]
[ 3 1 2 1 ] argsort .               \ [ 1 3 2 0 ] ties keep index order
[ "pear" "apple" "plum" ] argsort . \ [ 1 0 2 ]
[ "z" 3 1 "a" ] argsort .           \ [ 2 1 3 0 ] tag order: floats before strings
[ 7 ] argsort .                     \ [ 0 ]
[ ] argsort .                       \ [ ]
[ 3 1 2 ] dup argsort drop .        \ [ 3 1 2 ] source unchanged

\ === errors ===
5 argsort . cr                      \ error: not a matrix
[ 1 2 3 4 ] 2 2 matrix argsort . cr \ error: only vectors argsort

clear
\ array>set ( array -- set ): one sorted pass (val_cmp) + dedup, O(n log n).
\ Sorts by val_cmp, dedups equal elements, and does not mutate the source array.

\ === ordering and dedup on floats ===
[ 3 1 2 ] array>set . cr                       \ < 1 2 3 >
[ 1 2 3 ] array>set . cr                       \ < 1 2 3 >    already sorted
[ 3 2 1 ] array>set . cr                       \ < 1 2 3 >    reversed
[ ] array>set . cr                             \ < >          empty
[ 5 ] array>set . cr                           \ < 5 >        singleton
[ 7 7 7 7 ] array>set . cr                     \ < 7 >        all duplicates collapse
[ 3 1 2 1 3 2 ] array>set size . cr            \ 3            dedup count
[ -2 0 -5 3 -2 ] array>set . cr                \ < -5 -2 0 3 >  negatives, with a dup

\ === strings sort lexicographically and dedup by content ===
[ "c" "a" "b" "a" ] array>set . cr             \ < "a" "b" "c" >

\ === mixed types sort by tag (symbol < float < string) ===
[ "x" 5 :a ] array>set . cr                    \ < :a 5 "x" >

\ === null (T_NONE) sorts first and dedups ===
[ null 1 null 2 ] array>set size . cr          \ 3            two nulls collapse to one

\ === structural dedup of nested collections ===
[ [ 1 2 ] [ 1 2 ] ] array>set size . cr        \ 1            equal arrays dedup
[ [ 1 2 ] [ 1 3 ] ] array>set size . cr        \ 2            distinct arrays kept
[ < 1 2 > < 2 1 > ] array>set size . cr        \ 1            equal sets dedup

\ === the source array is not mutated ===
[ 3 1 2 ] dup array>set drop . cr              \ [ 3 1 2 ]    original order intact

\ === the result is a genuine set: membership and set ops work ===
[ 3 1 2 ] array>set 2 member? . cr             \ 1
[ 3 1 2 ] array>set 9 member? . cr             \ 0
[ 3 1 2 ] array>set < 2 3 4 > intersection . cr  \ < 2 3 >
[ 3 1 2 1 ] array>set < 1 2 3 > = . cr         \ 1            equal to the set literal

\ === scale: sorts and dedups at size ===
0 9999 range array>set size . cr               \ 10000
0 9999 range reverse array>set 1 take 0 @i . cr  \ 0          smallest first after the sort
0 100 range  0 100 range  concat  array>set size . cr   \ 101  the doubled range dedups

clear
\ add-last! ( arr v -- arr ) appends at the end, doubling the backing buffer when
\ full, and leaves the array. remove-last! ( arr -- v ) removes and returns the
\ last element. Together they grow and shrink an array in amortized O(1).

\ append leaves the grown array
[ 1 2 3 ] 4 add-last! . cr                      \ [ 1 2 3 4 ]

\ grows past the initial capacity
[ 1 2 ] 3 add-last! 4 add-last! 5 add-last! . cr  \ [ 1 2 3 4 5 ]

\ size and indexing track the growth
[ 1 2 ] 3 add-last! 4 add-last! size . cr       \ 4
[ 1 2 ] 3 add-last! 4 add-last! 3 @i . cr       \ 4

\ append onto an empty array
[ ] 1 add-last! . cr                            \ [ 1 ]

\ mutates in place: a bound array reflects the append
[ 1 2 ] to grow-me
grow-me 3 add-last! drop  grow-me . cr          \ [ 1 2 3 ]

\ stack shape: ( arr v -- arr ), items below are left alone
7 [ 1 2 ] 3 add-last! . cr
.s

clear
\ remove-last! returns the last element and shrinks the array in place
[ 1 2 3 ] to shrink-me
shrink-me remove-last! . cr                     \ 3
shrink-me size . cr                             \ 2
shrink-me . cr                                  \ [ 1 2 ]

\ round-trip: append then remove returns the appended value
[ 1 ] 2 add-last! remove-last! . cr             \ 2

\ remove down to empty, then removing again errors
[ 9 ] to one-el
one-el remove-last! . cr                        \ 9
one-el size . cr                                \ 0
one-el remove-last!                             \ error: empty array

\ failures
5 4 add-last!                                   \ error: not an array
[ ] remove-last!                                \ error: empty array

clear
\ first / second ( arr/pair -- v ): element 0/1 of an array; a cons's
\ head/tail.
[ 7 8 9 ] first . cr                            \ 7
[ 7 8 9 ] second . cr                           \ 8
5 6 cons first . cr                             \ 5
5 6 cons second . cr                            \ 6
[( 1 2 3 )] first . cr                          \ 1
[( 1 2 3 )] second . cr                         \ [( 2 3 )]  (the tail)
[ "a" ] first . cr                              \ a

\ errors
[ "a" ] second                                  \ (index out of bounds)
[ ] first                                       \ (index out of bounds)
5 first                                         \ (neither array nor pair)

bye
